He added: 'Our research detailing the molecular structure of the enzyme now enables a search for new KMO inhibitors that are able to cross the blood-brain barrier.

'This provides real hope for developing drug therapies to target neurodegenerative diseases such as Huntington's, Alzheimer's and Parkinson's diseases.'

Dr Flaviano Giorgini, the team's neurogeneticist from the University of Leicester, said: 'This is a big move forward for the development of new KMO inhibiting drugs.

