- Professor Sarah Tabrizi

'It is hoped that such compounds may ultimately be tested in clinical trials and prove beneficial for patients.'

The findings from the research will now be used in the search for more effective treatments for Huntington's Disease.

Professor Sarah Tabrizi, head of the Huntington's disease research team at University College London's Institute for Neurology, said: 'Unlocking the crystal structure of KMO is a real boost to our efforts to find treatments for this devastating disease.

'It provides a solid basis for the optimisation of inhibitor drugs like UPF 648 that are being developed by the global Huntington's disease research community.

'KMO is one of our top drug targets, and the crystal structure is a significant step along our roadmap to clinical trials of KMO inhibitors in patients.'

Cath Stanley, chief executive of the Huntington's Disease Association, also welcomed the findings.

She said: 'This research is a really exciting piece of the jigsaw that enables us to understand a little more and takes us a step closer to being able to provide an effective treatment for Huntington's Disease.'

